  "text": "The incidence of pheochromocytoma in the general population is 0.8% per 100 000 people and is often not diagnosed or managed by many internists, endocrinologist and nephrologists [CITATION_1] . We describe a case of a woman who develops an adrenergic crisis precipitated by glucocorticoid administration for an allergic reaction. Excess catecholamine release caused hypertension, type A non-ketotic lactic acidosis and non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema. After initiation of intravenous antihypertensive medications and suspected catecholamine depletion, the patient developed cardiogenic shock from myocarditis. Ischemic acute tubular necrosis was diagnosed after the above events occurred, however, it is postulated that she could have experience a decreased glomerular filtration rate from intense vasoconstriction of afferent arterioles due to excessive norepinephrine release. Fortunately, the patient made a full recovery but there are several teaching points that can be highlighted from this case report.",
